Food services celebrates Black Hist. Mo.

Christal Hall

Staff Writer

The beat of African djembe drums
echoed off the walls in the Towers
lobby as the alluring smell of chicken,
the smell of greens and macaroni &
cheese greeted students at the door of
the Towers Cafeteria. b

Over 200 voices talking, laughing
and singing ﬂoated up the stairway
leading down to the cafeteria. Photos
of different Africans and African
Americans peppered the corridor at
the bottom of the steps.

Among the pictures was a photo
of a slave who was beaten so horribly
that the lash marks from the whip
never healed properly. You could
count the number of times his back
had been torn open.

Karin Harris, a local vender,
greeted students at the end of the hall
as they entered the cafeteria, offering
to sell renderings of famous African
Americans etched in marble, granite,
tile and fabric.

Beyond was Pitt Food Service’s
and the Black Action Society’s 9th
annual black history month celebra-
tion. It also served as a culmination of
the month's events.

The day's festivities included a
performance from student rap group
Third World Theory and a step show
from Delta Sigma Theta and Alpha
Phi Alpha.

Audience members danced to the

enthusiastic polyrhythms of a Kenyan
music group, J abali Afrika.

Darick Thomas, a Sodexho
employee, said the event was to focus
on the unity of African Americans in
the community through a better
understanding of black history.

Abdou Cole, the coordinator and
founder of the event, said the celebra-
tion was to honor all of Pitt’s African
Americans, from janitors to profes-
sors.

“I wanted to put their name and
pictures up,” Cole said, “but for secu-
rity reasons I was not allowed to.”

Cole said the event was to height-
en cultural awareness. He reminisced
about a girl who came to last year’s
event, saying she was a high school
student in a youth group, Inner Circle.

He said that when the girl came to
the event she didn’t want to go to col-
lege, but after seeing this celebration
of diversity she went home to her
mother, raving about how much she
really wanted to attend college
because of everything she saw at the
presentation.

Elementary and high school stu-
dents danced and clapped along with
the Pitt students.

JaNay Queen brought a youth
group that she mentors, Vision
Incentives, to see the performers.

“I wanted the kids to see their
people doing some positive, instead
of standing on the street corners,”
Queen said.

