IFC and Pcmhel host
anti-alcohol party

Jason Galllnger
Staff Wrlter

Shilo Raube said she doesn’t
think there is a problem with alco-
hol at Pitt. '

So why were she and other
members of Delta Delta Delta
sorority at a party promoting ways
of having fun without alcohol?

“It’s always a good idea to do
these things to prevent there from
ever being a problem,” she said.

That was the prevailing theme
of the AAA/Pitt Greeks Mix—off
yesterday evening. It was sponsored
by the American Automobile
Association of Western
Pennsylvania and West Virginia and
Pitt Greeks.

Sororities and fraternities set up
tables in the ballroom of the
William Pitt Union where they
served non—alcoholic “mocktails.”
The drinks were judged on their
originality and taste while the
tables were rated according to how
much enthusiasm went into their
decoration.

Chi Omega, Phi Kappa Sigma
and Sigma Alpha Mu share the tro-
phy for best taste. The most spirited
drink award went to Delta Delta
Delta and Theta Chi. Most original
drink honors went to Sigma Alpha
Epsilon. And the tables with the
best themes were those of Alpha
Epsilon Phi, Delta Phi and Triangle.

More than 100 people turned

out for the party, including Pitt‘

Police Chief Deborah Furka.

Larry Geubtner of AAA agreed
with Raube that alcohol is not a
major problem at Pitt. Alcohol-
related problems at other schools,
however, prompted AAA to bring
its message here.

While it might have made more
sense to have the party closer to the
weekend to show how serious the
participants really were, Geubtner
said Tuesday was the only day the
room was available.

Brian Rakowiecki and Jeff
Riegelnegg served a drink they
called Fire and Ice, made with
peach sherbet and ginger ale, from
Sigma Alpha Epsilon’s table. They
both heartily agreed that the event
was a good idea.

“People think of frats and they
usually think of ‘Animal House,”’
Riegelnegg said. “This event helps
to dispel that negative image.”

“This is the perfect environment
to show people that they don’t need
alcohol to have a good time,”
Rakowiecki said.

“We want to send the message
that you don’t need to put alcohol
into a drink to make it taste good,”
Valerie Peterson of AAA said.

And the message seemed to be
getting across.

“This event is awesome,” Raube
said. “It’s a lot of fun.”

  
 

