the William Pitt Union Ballroom. It may be stu-
dents’ only chance to make their voices heard
and to get answers to serious questions, such as:

- If enrollment increases again next semester,
will the Department of Housing start cutting
beds in half to make room? Is Housing prepared
to deal with the real possibility that enrollment
will continue to rise? Will it continue to guaran-
tee students three years of campus housing?

0 What would it take to have a cafeteria besides
Schenley Cafe open for some reasonable length
of time on the weekends? How about keeping
something open all night through the week, like
Eddies’ or the cafeteria below Towers, so hungry
students cramming through all-nighters won’t-
have to live off candy bars from the vending
machines?

0 Speaking of 24-hour availability, what would
it take to have Student Health Services remain
open all night, or at the very least, on the week-
ends? The whole point of paying a student health
fee every semester is so that students can get
medical assistance when they need it while
avoiding expensive hospital bills. But that won’t
work for someone who sprains his ankle at 9
p.m. and has to either hike up the hill to UPMC
or call for an expensive ambulance ride.

These are only a few of the problems that
need to be addressed. Surely everyone has a
peeve they feel the University could fix. But
nothing will change unless students make an
effort to talk to the people in charge.

