Fall of U.S.S.R. didn't leave U.S. invincible

Paul Clark
Columnist

An unfortunate fallacy that per-
vades popular thought is that only
the former Soviet Union and the
United States possess nuclear
weapons. A cursory Who’s Who
among nuclear nations should sur-
prise and scare some of you:

According to the International
Institute for Strategic Studies,
France holds 449 active nuclear war-
heads while the United Kingdom
has 260. A defected high-ranking
nuclear technician, Mordechai
Vanunu, testiﬁed that Israel has
manufactured 300 atomic bombs
and has color photographs to prove
it. South Africa, who has not signed
the NPT (Nuclear Non-Proliferation
Treaty), as of 1988 controls 20
nuclear bombs. One may not feel
especially endangered by this since
the above nations have been por-
trayed in the media as “good”
nations (in relation with the United
States and other “good” nations).

But what about these guys?
India bears between 12 and 20
nuclear warheads, while their neigh-
bor, Pakistan, competes with four. A
war and nuclear holocaust between
these two unfriendly nations remains
a distinct possibility. Both have been
in a mini-race for a decade, and now
India has the Prithvi missile, which
is capable of carrying a nuclear war-
head deep into Pakistan. Casualties,
even with such a small number of
bombs, would be tremendous (due
to the high densities of people) and
eventual United Nations involve-
ment would probably be necessary.
UN involvement means U.S. sol-
diers. Clearly, nuclear arms build-up
by these nations does not bode well
for their citizens or ours.

Most frightening of all may be
the current nuclear situation in com-
munist North Korea. While reports
from defectors have estimated the
DPRK’s stockpile as high as 50, the
CLA conﬁrms their possession of at
least 10 fully—operational nuclear
warheads, as of 1995, and this num-
ber may be growing. Combined, the
DPRK’s nuclear reactors have the
capacity to produce 45 nuclear
bombs a year.

Further, fully—operational
nuclear warheads mean that they are
ready to be ﬁtted on to nuclear-carri-
able missiles. The DPRK boasts a
plentiful supply of over 300
NoDong-l’s and NoDong-2’s with
ranges of 1,300 km and 1,500 km,
respectively. This makes Japan very
nervous. In addition, the DPRK has
thousands of short range Scud-B/C
missiles. This makes South Korea
very nervous. The U.S. Defense
Intelligence Agency (DIA) veriﬁes
that the DPRK also boasts a small
number of Taepo-Dong-2 ICBMs
with a maximum range of 6,200
miles (with a small nuclear warhead
attached). The missile could easily
reach all major west coast cities,
including Los

in the United States nervous yet?

Especially worrisome is that the
DPRK’s dictator Kim Jong II has a
vendetta against South Korea and its
allies (namely the US) and just isn’t
known to be a stable person. He, like
his father, has not allowed the
United Nations’ IAEA inspectors to
any nuclear reactor sites or suspect-
ed bunkers. Little wonder that we
are preparing to strike Iraq (with no
such capabilities) instead of anger-
ing the DPRK who could wipe out
LA.

Another remaining factor in our

