A few ﬁnal facts: Despite
promising otherwise, Russia has
continued testing its nuclear
weapons. Late last year, a seismic
tremor was detected in Russia — a
clear indication of underground test-
ing. The denials came swiftly while
Russian ofﬁcials blamed a small
earthquake. This earthquake just
happened to take place nearby a for-
mer Soviet nuclear test site, coinci-
dentally. Hmmm.

Articles from Russia boast of
new technology that they developed
to produce “miniature neutron
bombs no bigger than a baseball.”
The current lack of security in
Russia and the vast terrorist market
for such an item (IRA, Iraq, Iran,
Palestine, Hamas, etc.) holds
unimaginable consequences.

Simply put, when considering
only the vast nuclear dangers facing
this nation, the wrong answer to mil-
itary questions could translate into
millions of casualties. The United
States must keep the pace with rapid
technological advances in nuclear
weaponry and the changing nuclear
capabilities of nations. Blindly advo-
cating freezes and reductions in mil-
itary spending clearly represents the
wrong direction for defending our-
selves.

