Dig into those pockets; it's iuncirising season!

It’s about this time every year that
America falls under siege by a rather
surgically effective and unsurpassable
force: the Girl Scouts of America annu-
al cookie drive.

There is really no way for the aver-
age Joe to avoid this army of midget
beret-sporting warriors who attack with
precision and the most psychologically
overwhelming tactic known to mankind:
cuteness. This year, I have already fallen
prey to one of their soft—spoken
demands of unconditional surrender: the
classic, “You mean you only want two
boxes of Chocolate Thin Mints?”

How could I possibly turn down a
group of sweet little Girl Scouts with a
wide-blinking-eyed-cuteness-factor a
thousand times greater than that of
Bambi and Thumper combined? By the
time these pygmy tacticians turned
around and skipped away with my next
paycheck and an order for two metric
tons of cookies, I realized that I too had
become their victim.

Yes, how the mighty have fallen for
a case of Do—Si-Dos. (Oh, you sweet lit-
tle oatmeal peanut butter cremes, natu-
rally good with no artiﬁcial ﬂavors and
no artiﬁcial colors.)

The bottom line is that these little
girls could be selling arsenic pills and
most people would still end up buying
several packs “just to have around the
house.” The Girl Scouts of America is
an organization with a cookie—selling
public relations machine so strong that
they have even named their junior mem-
bers “Brownies.” And Brownies are

organized in
“troops.” And you
still think I’m
wrong about this
whole militant
cookie-sales phi-
losophy, folks?

But I don’t
want to pick on
just the Girl Scouts because many peo-
ple view those who do this in the same
fashion they do as, say, individuals who
club baby dolphins for fun and sport.

No matter who you are, you either
have been or will one day ﬁnd yourself
in an organized group. Once in such an
organization, you quickly realize that in
order to do anything more than meet in
the hallway of a McDonald’s every
Tuesday night and watch industrial
strength cleanser congeal, you need
money. This having been said, in every
group there is one person who eventual-
ly raises his hand and offers a suggestion
to the effect of “Hey, let’s sell candy as
a fundraiser. It will be fun!”

About the time this person starts
changing this motto to “Ve haf Veys of
making you sell candy,” he is henceforth
known as your group’s fundraising nazi.

The fundraising nazi makes sure
you sell, under penalty of severe casti-
gation involving a case of Skittles, no
clothes and a tennis ball pitching
machine. He soon hands you a case of
candy that comes in one of two easy—to—
sell forms: 1) brand name candy, but
comparable in si_ze and weight to that of
a small piece of hockey equipment or 2)

A MARC
Nuzzo

 

a generic brand undis-
tinguishable‘ from
everyday bathroom
grout. Needless to
say, these will both
sell for anywhere
from $1 to $2 per
ounce.

So there you are, stuck holding the
box. One part of you always wants to
leave it on the small dolly you use to tote
it around. The other half of you knows
that if you do this the fundraiser nazi
will make you fork out $354.23 for your
$25 ticket to this year’s national conven-
tion. So rather than ﬂee the country or
do something really difﬁcult like quit
the Webster’s Dictionary Fan Club, you
lash out at the people closest to you in a
formal social setting: your co-workers.

There are several ways in which to
try and sell fundraising candy at work.
The first, and least aggressive, is the
“spring trap” method. Using this
method, you set the box out in the mid-
dle of a table near a very public place,
such as a coffee machine or water cool-
er. During breaks, unsuspecting cowork-
ers wander in, see the box, and open it.
It is at this point that the trap goes off
and the prey is caught.

The ‘seller —- casually" and conve-
niently hanging around the box -
quickly chirps out something like, “Oh,
those are $2.50 each. Thanks so much,
Jimmy will be able to get his transplant
now.” At this point, the victim must
either shell out the cash or allow himself
to be categorized in the same group as

COLUMNIST

people who make fun of Girl Scouts.

Boom. Sale.

ﬁe next method is to actively walk
around and sell the items. Normally, the
higher up you are on the corporate food
chain, the fewer cubicles you’ll have to
walk to before you are sold out.
Whereas a gofer may have to walk
around the entire ﬂoor of the ofﬁce, a
manager normally need not walk any
further than his poop—listed employee’s
cubicles.

Ca-ching.

The ﬁnal way is the most aggressive
and risky. It involves opening the box
and pitching the candy at people in the
ofﬁce at the same velocity as a surface
to air missle. When the pack tears open
after bashing into their skull or ricochet-
ing off their elbow, you simply run over
and stemly say “Hey, look. You just
opened that. I hope you are planning to
pay for it.”

No matter what method people
choose to sell their fundraising products,
the ultimate goal is to return all money
to the fundraising nazi. Do not pass go,
but collect $200 so you can buy your
ﬁrst-bom back from the fundraising
nazi. Most importantly, don’t ever forget
that you’re in this organization because
you voluntarily want to be there.

Be there, that is, until next spring or
the Girl Scouts come around again ——
whichever comes ﬁrst. '

