The Pitt men’s and women’s track
teams went to their respective regional
championship meets last weekend, and
each came home champions.

The women went to the ECAC
championships in Boston. The top per-
formances at the meet came in the 4x800
meter relay team and Trecia Smith in the
shot put. The relay team of Joetta Purter,
Chantee Earl, Shauna McFadzean and
Tamika Dorin won first place and set a
school record of 8:54.33.

. Head Coach Steve Lewis had partic-
ular praise for McFadzean’s perfor-
mance.

“[McFadzean] had a personal record
twice, in the trials and in the finals. She
did a fantastic job,” Lewis said.

Unfortunately for the Panthers, the
4x800 meter relay is not run at the
national championship meet. However,

A Earl has qualified on her own in the 800

meters and will make the trip to the
national meet in Indianapolis next week-
end.

The only Panther athlete accompa-
nying her will be Smith. Smith won the
shot put at the ECAC meet with a throw
of 48- 1/2, her best ever.

THE PITT NEWS

Earl, Smith qualify for track nationals

And it’s not even her best event. She
earned a trip to nationals with perfor-
mances in the long jump and triple jump
earlier in the season.

Other top performances for the
women included Anna Kohler’s 2:52.23
in the 1000 meters, placing her third in
the East.

Ayana Coleman, who won the pen-
tathlon at the Big East championships as
a freshman two weeks ago, came back
with another strong showing, coming in
fourth in the region with 3462 points.
Kianga Lee, who was second behind
Coleman in the conference, finished
eighth with 3168. Teammate Gina
Bundy was 10th with 2801.

The men’s team, competing in the
IC4A championship meet at Cornell, got
a measure of revenge for a subpar per-
formance at the Big East championships
two weeks before. Despite having few
standout individual performances, the
team finished 11th out of 72 teams at the
meet. The Panthers finished higher than
several teams that beat them at the Big
East meet, including West Virginia and
perennial powerhouse Villanova.

Pitt did that without their top indi-
vidual performer, .hurdler Aranthes
Lewin. Lewin stayed out of the meet due
to a hamstring injury.

The only individuals to finish in the
top eight (and thus score points for the
team) for Pitt were Sekou Dilday and
Carl Taylor. Dilday was third in the 400
meters with a time of 48.36 seconds.
Taylor finished sixth in the 500 meters
with 1:04.23.

Pitt’s Tim Tyre also qualified for the
finals of the 400 meters but finished just
out of a scoring position in 10th place.

“Tim ran well in the trials, not so
well in the finals. Then he came back
and ran very well in his relay,” said Pitt
Assistant Coach Dave Sobal.

The mile relay team provided the
rest of Pitt’s points. Dilday, Tyre and
Taylor ran the final three legs. In the trial
heats, Jeremy Ward led off, but he was
replaced in the finals by Greg Blake.

“All five of those guys deserve cred-
it,” Sobal said. “The trials were tough.
The times were really close in there.”

In a photo finish, Taylor put Pitt in
first place ahead of Connecticut by .33
seconds. Pitt’s winning time was a track
record 3:13.36.

The indoor season for the men is
now finished, as no men have qualified
for the national championship meet. The
first meet of Pitt’s outdoor season for
both men and women will be March 26-
29 at Alabama.

